I&#39;m not sure how intensive creating a `LinearGradient` is on a phone, but if that&#39;s not an issue, you can just make `LinearGradient` a computed variable:

    var color1 = &quot;1a&quot;
    var color2 = &quot;1b&quot;

    let cardGradient: LinearGradient {
        LinearGradient(gradient: Gradient(colors: [Color(color1), Color(color2)]), startPoint: .leading, endPoint: .trailing)
    }

If it is intensive on computing resources, you can .make it optional (or give it a default value) and set it in the `.onAppear` of a view, but then you would have to make the gradient `@State`:

    var color1 = &quot;1a&quot;
    var color2 = &quot;1b&quot;
    @State var cardGradient: LinearGradient?
    
    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            // ... some views here
        }.onAppear {
            self.cardGradient = LinearGradient(gradient: Gradient(colors: [Color(color1), Color(color2)]), startPoint: .leading, endPoint: .trailing)
        }
    }

Keep in mind that both these solutions aren&#39;t particularly great for if the colors often change, but you don&#39;t want to gradient to update when the colors change, however it doesn&#39;t sound like that is an issue for you. If you see lag with the first option, use the second one.

